title: Moorhouse
description:
Moorhouse is a large office building in the City of London. It is located on the eastern edge of the financial district and is one of the largest buildings in the area, standing 84 metres 18 stories tall with two basement floors and with 29,112 square metres of floorspace (of which 2,134 square metres are retail space and 26,978 square metres are office space.

Constructed from 2002 to 2004, it is the first building to be designed for the London Crossrail, with a shaft to the station underneath the building. It has the deepest foundations in London, which reach down 57 metres and are specifically designed to withstand further tunneling below it in the future. The building also has 14 lifts, and its design allows the potential to add three shuttle lifts running between the first and fourth floors.

The building's architect is Sir Norman Foster.

It is built on the former site of a 67-metre 18-floor office building that stood from 1961 to 2001.

title: Tower House
description:
Tower House was a working class jewel in the East End of London during the early 19th Century. A respite from the squalid conditions of disease-ridden lodgings around the area, Tower House provided a safe and relatively clean place to put your head down for a night.

Built in 1902 under the vision and philanthropy of Lord Rowton, Tower House was the fifth development from the Rowton Houses scheme. Lord Rowton, troubled by the conditions he saw on the streets of London, wanted to provide cheap accommodation for the poorly paid. He wanted to provide something that surpassed anything that was on offer at the time for the working man.

 Joseph Stalin spent a fortnight in a sixpence-a-night cubicle in Tower House in 1907, when he attended the Fifth Congress of the Russian Social Democratic Labour Party across the road in Whitechapel Road, which consolidated the supremacy of the Bolshevik Party.

Writer Jack London called it the "Monster Doss House" in People of the Abyss, his 1902 journey through the poverty of London. He said it was packed with "life that is degrading and unwholesome".

George Orwell, in Down and Out in Paris and London, published in 1933, described it as the best of all common-lodging houses, with "excellent bathrooms". Orwell's only objections to the shilling-a-night rent were the "no cards, no cooking" rules and harsh discipline. No one was admitted before 7pm. 


In 2005 it went through extensive renovations and is now offers chic and expensive loft-style flats, which is a shame considering its original purposes

title: Sadlers Wells theatre
description:
Sadlers Wells lies at the end of the New River (1600s) and is a dance/theatre venue.

Sadler's Wells Theatre is the name of six theatres that have been built since 1683 at a site on Rosebery Avenue, Clerkenwell in the London Borough of Islington. title: Tower 42
description:
Tower 42 is a skyscraper in the City of London. The original name was National Westminster Tower (or NatWest Tower), having been built to house the bank's international division. When the tower is seen from above, it closely resembles the NatWest logo. The tower was designed by Richard Seifert, engineered by Pell Frischmann, constructed from 1971 to 1980 by John Mowlem and Co. at a cost of £72,000,000, and formally opened on 11 July 1981 by Queen Elizabeth II.

The tower has 47 floors, 42 of which are cantlevered, with 2 underground floors, and its height of 183 m (600 ft) made it the tallest building in the UK from 1980 until 1991 and the tallest building in the City of London until 2011. It has a floor area of 30,100 sq m (323,994 sq ft). The floorplates are cantilevered from a huge concrete core, giving the building great strength but significantly limiting the amount of available floor space. The core contains 13 elevators. The lowest cantilevered floor is designated as Level 1, but is actually the 4th floor above ground. The cantilevered floors are designated as three segments, or leaves. The two lowest cantilevered levels are formed of a single leaf, while the next two are formed of two leaves. This pattern is repeated at the top, so that only levels 5-38 extend around the whole of the core. The cantilever was constructed to take advantage of the air rights granted to this and the neighbouring site whilst respecting the banking hall on the adjacent site.

Innovative features in the tower's design include double-deck elevators, a sky lobby (at floors 23-24), an internal automated "mail train", and an automated external window-washing system.

On 24 April 1993, the tower was extensively damaged by a truck bomb which detonated in the Bishopsgate area. From 1994 to 1996, it had to be externally reclad and internally refurbished. Afterwards, NatWest decided not to reoccupy, had the building renamed International Financial Centre, and then sold it. The new owners, Greycoat, gave the building its current name. It is now a general-purpose office building occupied by a variety of companies. Tower 42 also has three restaurants: One on ground level, one on the 24th floor, and one on the 42nd floor.

title: BlackRock
description:
BlackRock® is a premier provider of global investment management services. 
Through BlackRock Solutions®, the firm provides risk management and advisory services that combine capital markets expertise with proprietarily-developed systems and technology. BlackRock was founded in 1988 on the belief that experienced professionals using a disciplined investment process and sophisticated analytical tools can consistently add value to client portfolios.  The most significant step in this process has been the merger with Merrill Lynch Investment Managers (MLIM), which occurred in September 2006. 
BlackRock is independent in ownership and governance, with no single majority stockholder and a majority of independent directors. In terms of equity, Merrill Lynch’s stake is approximately 49%, while PNC Financial Services Group retains an interest of about 34%; the remaining 17% is held by BlackRock employees and the public. BlackRock serves clients in North and South America, Europe, Asia, Australia and the Middle East. Headquartered in New York, the firm maintains offices in 18 countries around the world.

title: 1 Commercial Street
description: This large tower block designed by Seifert architects, which is on top of the entrance to Aldgate East underground station, was abandoned half way through construction after Landsbanki (the Icelandic bank) went bankrupt and was unable to finance the remaining construction work.  Several celebrities are known to have invested in this project and look set to lose much, or all, of their investment.  It was set to include 10 stories of offices (approx 10,000 metres of space) and 217 apartments above, but construction stopped at the 11th floor and the site has been abandoned for several months, with cranes and equipment removed from the site.  As the recession deepens (as of February 2009) it is very unclear if it will ever be finished.
